## 3) Hyperlane Manipulation (Infrastructure-Driven Route Control)

### Goal
Allow deliberate, planning-focused creation/removal/modification of connections without enabling instant “combat trap” reactions.

### Primary Anchor
Starbase module/building as the control surface (territorial, time-gated, costed, readable in war).

### Required/Approved Constraints
- Distance limit: actions only allowed to targets within a configured range.
- Target selection menu: when initiating an action, the player selects the target connection (e.g., pick a target system/neighbor from an event-driven list).
- Not reactive cheese: actions should be slow/telegraphed and/or restricted while contested.

### Optional Concepts (include in scope)
- Per-use action cost (in addition to module construction): each create/delete/modify action can consume resources (influence, alloys, energy, unity, etc.), take time (project/situation), and have cooldowns.
- Interdiction alternative: a wartime-friendly module effect that slows/penalizes hostile transit instead of deleting lanes (supports strategy without topology breakage).
- Visual representation (optional): if physical “pylons” are desired, spawn them only for engineered corridors rather than at every hyperlane endpoint to avoid early-game clutter.

### Guardrails (recommended; not yet finalized)
These are additional constraints discussed to keep manipulation strategic and avoid unfair fleet traps:
- No instant collapse: deletion should be a long project/situation with warning time.
- No deletion while contested: restrict deletion in systems that are occupied/contested/recently fought in, and/or when hostile fleets are present.
- Do not isolate the map: do not allow deletions that disconnect components or leave systems with zero exits.
- Throughput limits: one engineering action at a time per starbase; optional empire-wide caps/cooldowns.
- Prefer wartime control via interdiction; reserve true topology edits for slow, deliberate changes.

### Kilo/Megastructure Discussion Summary
- Per-hyperlane-endpoint kilo-structures are flavorful but likely bookkeeping-heavy and potentially performance/UI noisy.
- System-level infrastructure (starbase module/building or a single in-system construct) is preferred; if visuals are used, keep them sparse and tied to engineered edges only.

### Risks / Tests
- High risk category: connectivity breakage, AI confusion, MP determinism.
- Tests: prevent isolation; enforce deletion restrictions; verify pathing; verify that actions are time-gated and not instantaneous.

